SIMPLE: sneeze
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sneeze
<hw>Sneeze</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Sneezed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sneezing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>snesen</ets>; of
uncertain origin; cf. D. <ets>snuse</ets> to sniff, E. <ets>neese</ets>,
and AS. <ets>fne⟦oacute⟧san</ets>.]</ety> <def>To emit air, chiefly
through the nose, audibly and violently, by a kind of involuntary
convulsive force, occasioned by irritation of the inner membrane of the
nose.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Not to be sneezed at</b></col>, <cd>not to be despised or
contemned; not to be treated lightly.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧He had to do with old women who were <xex>not to be sneezed
at</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Prof. Wilson.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sneeze</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sneeze
<hw>Sneeze</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A sudden and violent ejection of air
with an audible sound, chiefly through the nose.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sneezeweed</ent>⟦br⟧
